Being an introverted creative and valuing one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark from that service, be available around the clock, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it's a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and push it on everyone. I'm looking for new ways to run my business while simultaneously fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do things a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I have canceled FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better GDPR support and will be moving my business there in the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google anything for normal email validation.
3/3
